  "prompt": "How long do women spend shaving every week compared to the 50s?",
  "response": "The amount of time women spend shaving can vary significantly based on individual preferences, routines, and technological advancements in grooming tools. In the 1950s, shaving was a common method for hair removal, but likely more time-consuming due to the limited availability of advanced razors and products.\n\nToday, women might spend different amounts of time shaving based on their personal grooming habits and preferences. Advancements such as electric razors, high-quality manual razors, and more effective shaving creams and gels can reduce the time spent on shaving. Additionally, alternatives like waxing, laser hair removal, and depilatory creams contribute to varied time commitments for hair removal processes.\n\nOn average, if a woman shaves several times a week, she might spend around 5-10 minutes per session, potentially resulting in approximately 15-30 minutes per week. In contrast, in the 1950s, this routine might have taken longer due to the manual process and less efficient tools available.\n\nFor precise comparisons, more detailed studies or surveys would be needed to quantify exact time differences.",
